In December, @SebastianCaliri and Finn Kennedy of @8VC wrote about how autonomous healthcare AI is "banned de facto or de jure in the United States." Some blockers included: state practice acts that don't recognize AI practitioners, FDA approval pathways not designed for autonomous systems, and no reimbursement mechanism to make innovation investable. It asked for @CMSGov to create outcome-aligned payments through CMMI, for @US_FDA to reform its approach, and for states to pass Medical AI Practice Acts.

I've enjoyed reading this piece several times since publication. It's thoughtful, detailed, and directionally right. And a lot has happened in the two months since publication!

@CMSGov announced the ACCESS Model: outcome-aligned payments for technology-enabled chronic care management, starting July 2026.

@US_FDA launched TEMPO alongside ACCESS, providing regulatory flexibility for AI tools used within the model.

@ARPA_H announced ADVOCATE: a program to develop the first FDA-authorized clinical agentic AI that can autonomously manage cardiovascular disease, including writing and modifying prescriptions. The federal government is now actively funding autonomous AI care delivery.

The @AmerMedicalAssn noted "it is time to explore modernized regulatory pathways".

HHS Deputy Secretary @HHS_Jim cited Utah's AI prescription program as "a great step forward" and signaled that FDA and CMS are building frameworks to support broader adoption.

Any one of these advancements would have been difficult to imagine 6 months ago.

Credit to our leadership for pushing forward in ways that are smart, safe, and effective. The blockers identified are real, but policymakers, clinicians, and innovators are now working together to address them. Open collaboration is how we can modernize healthcare for all Americans.

